  "summary": "Inspector Hakaste and Inspector Rune interrogate Miss Wat Tyler regarding the murder of a man who identified himself as \"Curry.\" Miss Wat Tyler denies knowing anyone by that name, though she notes that she and James hold insurance policies with the \"Mutual Insurance Association.\" She provides an alibi for James Watkinson, stating he was at \"Gatesford and Swindham's firm\" on Hay Street during the incident and typically eats lunch at \"The Three Feathers.\" As the detectives depart, Constable Lamb observes a golf club inside a baseball bag, an item Miss Wat Tyler claims she does not know how it arrived there.\n\nOutside, Hakaste and Lamb discuss the interrogation. Hakaste expresses suspicion regarding Miss Pembroke, noting a discrepancy in her walking route and suspecting she may have made a phone call at 1:58 PM, despite her denial.\n\nThe detectives then proceed to 20 Wilbraham Crescent, a poorly maintained property known as Diana Cottage. The house has a bright turquoise door and a pungent odor. Upon entering, they meet Mrs. Hemm, an elderly woman wearing an orange fur scarf that is actually a live cat. The residence is filled with several cats and a strong animal smell. Mrs. Hemm, who is defensive due to a complaint from the \"Prevention of Cruelty to Animals Association,\" expresses little interest in the murder at number 19, initially confusing the investigation with a matter involving a neighbor's dog.",
